    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Messrs Lewis May&#44; M Ellinger&#44; &#38; Mayer S. Isaacs.<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia May 14<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1876<lb/></p>
            <p>Gentlemen<lb/></p>
            <p>The Hebrew Ministers in our city&#44; to whom<lb/> your communication was directed&#44; met last evening<lb/> at the rooms of Y M H W.  Having appointed<lb/> the Revd Dr Samuel Hirsch chairman&#44; and S. Morais<lb/> secretary&#44; they proceeded to discuss the various questions<lb/> you have asked.  The following is substantially their<lb/> reply.<lb/></p>
            <p>1.	It is&#44; by all means&#44; advisable&#44; instead of establishing<lb/> a separate college in which secular as well as Hebrew learning<lb/> <del>shall</del> would be imparted&#44; that chairs for the teaching of sacred<lb/> literature be founded in some well&#45;known American university<lb/></p>
            <p>2.	The studies pursued ought to be&#58; &#40;a&#41; Select <del>portions</del> passages of<lb/> the Talmud with <sic>commentarie</sic> &#40;b&#41; The most difficult chapters<lb/> <del>passages</del> of the poetical books of the Bible&#44; elucidated by<lb/> the researches of modern critics. &#169; The chaldaic lan&#45;<lb/>&#45;guage&#44; and&#44; as far as attainable&#44; that of the Arabic and<lb/> kindred tongues. &#40;d&#41; Practical exercises in homelitics.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>These studies should be divided into different courses&#44;<lb/> allowing those students who simply wish to qualify themselves<lb/> for the position of Hebrew instructors to omit a portion thereof.<lb/></p>
            <p>3.	Before entering the University to pursue the studies afore&#45;<lb/>mentioned&#44; scholars should have learnt&#44; &#40;a&#41; the historical<lb/> books of Holy Writ&#44; in the original&#44; &#40;b&#41; the least difficult<lb/> passages <del>out of</del> from the Prophets and Psalms &#40;c&#41; <del>the rules</del><lb/> <del>of</del> Hebrew Grammar &#40;d&#41; one treatise of the 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> volume of<lb/> Maimonides &#40;Yad hacaza kah&#41;&#44; attesting their ability to<lb/> read understandingly without punctuations.<lb/></p>
            <p>4.	&#91;&#63;&#93; attending high&#45;schools&#44; and having received<lb/> some knowledge of Hebrew in institutions attached to or<lb/> disconnected from their respective congregations&#44; shall<lb/> attend in the afternoon or evening&#44; such schools&#44; in<lb/> which the branches designated above are imparted.<lb/>  To establish schools of that character&#44; and carry them<lb/> on successfully&#44; committees in each city where con&#45;<lb/>gregations contribute towards the furtherance of the<lb/> present object&#44; should be appointed to direct&#44; su&#45;<lb/>pervise&#44; and secure a uniform plan.<lb/></p>
            <p>5.	Competitive examinations are deemed an efficient<lb/> mode of exacting emulation&#44; and hence&#44; progress in<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>the study of the holy language<lb/></p>
            <p>6. With the exception of the chairman &#40;the Revd<lb/> Dr S. Hirsch&#41; the ministers present at the<lb/> meeting&#44; namely Drs Jastrow and <sic>Elllen</sic>&#44; &#38;<lb/> Messrs Jacobs &#38; Morais&#44; considered the question<lb/> of establishing a college&#44; or of chairs for the branches<lb/> named in &#40;1&#41; totally premature&#44; and consequently<lb/> impracticable for the present time.<lb/></p>
        </body>
